WEBVTT

00:06.366 --> 00:09.730
[ Low, humming music plays ]

00:09.730 --> 00:17.177
♪♪

00:17.177 --> 00:24.264
♪♪

00:24.264 --> 00:26.547
[ Music intensifies ]

00:26.547 --> 00:36.436
♪♪

00:36.436 --> 00:46.366
♪♪

00:46.366 --> 00:56.256
♪♪

00:56.256 --> 01:06.186
♪♪

01:06.186 --> 01:08.789
‐Don't do this.

01:08.789 --> 01:12.072
‐It's done. And it's final.

01:12.072 --> 01:14.875
♪♪

01:14.875 --> 01:18.118
‐Let me tell my crew.

01:18.118 --> 01:20.440
♪♪

01:20.440 --> 01:22.362
‐Go home.

01:22.362 --> 01:24.965
We'll show you the language
when it's ready.

01:24.965 --> 01:27.087
[ Dog tags clink ]

01:27.087 --> 01:35.295
♪♪

01:35.295 --> 01:43.544
♪♪

01:43.544 --> 01:51.752
♪♪

01:51.752 --> 02:00.000
♪♪

02:00.000 --> 02:08.248
♪♪

02:08.248 --> 02:10.010
[ Sighs ]

02:10.010 --> 02:18.659
♪♪

02:18.659 --> 02:27.307
♪♪

02:27.307 --> 02:29.630
[ Spigot sputters ]

02:35.756 --> 02:37.878
‐Okay. My turn.

02:39.920 --> 02:41.682
[ Grunts ]

02:41.682 --> 02:43.884
[ Light clicks ]

02:43.884 --> 02:46.246
[ Bolt squeaks ]

02:48.328 --> 02:52.292
[ Clatter, thunk ]

02:52.292 --> 02:54.494
[ Grunts, groans ]

03:14.034 --> 03:15.636
[ Snap ]

03:20.681 --> 03:22.242
[ Unlocks door,
door rattles ]

03:22.242 --> 03:24.084
[ Clatters, squeaks ]

03:24.084 --> 03:26.286
[ Thunk ]

03:33.534 --> 03:35.816
[ Thudding ]

03:35.816 --> 03:37.497
[ Cellphone buzzes ]

03:37.497 --> 03:39.740
‐Incoming call.

03:39.740 --> 03:41.942
[ Tools thunk heavily,
cellphone buzzes ]

03:41.942 --> 03:43.504
Incoming call.

03:43.504 --> 03:46.667
[ Cellphone buzzes ]

03:46.667 --> 03:48.068
‐[ Cellphone buzzes ]
‐Incoming call.

03:48.068 --> 03:50.150
‐[ Tone rings ]
‐Hagerty.

03:50.150 --> 03:52.633
‐Good morning, Captain Hagerty.
This is Aaron Shultz

03:52.633 --> 03:54.635
from The New York Times.
I was wondering if I could ‐‐

03:54.635 --> 03:57.157
‐How did you get this number?
‐We had it on file.

03:57.157 --> 03:58.519
A colleague of mine
did an interview a few years ‐‐

03:58.519 --> 04:00.561
‐Not doing press today.

04:00.561 --> 04:02.523
‐As the original commander of
the mission, would you like t‐‐

04:02.523 --> 04:04.244
‐End call.
‐[ Tone rings ]

04:15.175 --> 04:16.537
TV.

04:16.537 --> 04:18.539
Screen on.

04:18.539 --> 04:21.822
‐An estimated 2 billion people
are watching around the world

04:21.822 --> 04:23.704
to witness this
historic moment ‐‐

04:23.704 --> 04:27.147
the launch of the first
human mission to Mars.

04:27.147 --> 04:28.589
In just a few short hours,

04:28.589 --> 04:30.751
the five astronauts
of Providence 1

04:30.751 --> 04:33.674
will leave Earth to embark
on their 2 1/2‐year journey

04:33.674 --> 04:35.756
to Mars and back.

04:35.756 --> 04:37.758
We're now gonna take you
live to the launch center

04:37.758 --> 04:41.522
in Louisiana, where Laz Ingram,
the founder and CEO of VISTA,

04:41.522 --> 04:42.763
is joining us.

04:42.763 --> 04:44.204
Good morning, Ms. Ingram.

04:44.204 --> 04:45.566
‐[ British accent ]
Thanks for having me.

04:45.566 --> 04:47.407
‐It's been a long road
getting here.

04:47.407 --> 04:51.091
‐Yes, eight years since NASA
awarded us the Mars contract.

04:51.091 --> 04:52.613
Eight very challenging years.

04:52.613 --> 04:54.014
‐Walk us through
what we can expect

04:54.014 --> 04:56.376
in the days and months ahead.
‐Gladly.

04:56.376 --> 04:58.298
Once the crew
has achieved orbit,

04:58.298 --> 05:00.140
they'll dock with
the Mars Transit Vehicle.

05:00.140 --> 05:01.742
The astronauts will climb aboard

05:01.742 --> 05:03.664
and conduct
what we call a shakedown ‐‐

05:03.664 --> 05:05.826
a rigorous series
of diagnostic tests ‐‐

05:05.826 --> 05:07.868
and then they'll initiate
the first long burn,

05:07.868 --> 05:09.590
sending them on their way.

05:09.590 --> 05:12.112
Seven months later,
they'll arrive at Mars,

05:12.112 --> 05:13.634
descend to the surface,

05:13.634 --> 05:16.036
spend 18 months before
they launch in the MAV

05:16.036 --> 05:18.759
back to the Transit Vehicle
and make their journey home.

05:18.759 --> 05:20.681
But aside from
accomplishing the feats ‐‐

05:20.681 --> 05:21.682
‐Mute.

05:21.682 --> 05:23.363
[ Silence ]

05:23.363 --> 05:25.125
‐... the very first human
looked up at the stars

05:25.125 --> 05:27.327
and wondered in whatever
language she spoke on,

05:27.327 --> 05:29.530
"What is it? What's out there?"

05:29.530 --> 05:33.534
These are the answers
that we continue to search for.

05:33.534 --> 05:35.816
‐I just have to ask,
and I'm sure everyone else

05:35.816 --> 05:37.257
wants to know,

05:37.257 --> 05:39.580
what is going through
your mind right now?

05:42.142 --> 05:44.424
‐Too much to...

05:44.424 --> 05:48.148
How can I possibly reply?
That's irrelevant.

05:48.148 --> 05:50.631
‐But none of this would be
happening without you.

05:50.631 --> 05:53.514
Are you happy?
Nervous?

05:53.514 --> 05:57.878
‐I'm focused. We still have
a lot of work ahead of us.

05:57.878 --> 06:00.120
‐Well, congratulations,
Ms. Ingram.

06:00.120 --> 06:02.362
We know that you're busy
and need to get to the launch.

06:02.362 --> 06:04.765
Thanks for spending some time
with us this morning.

06:04.765 --> 06:07.568
‐It's been an absolute pleasure.
Thank you.

06:07.568 --> 06:09.249
‐And we're off.

06:09.249 --> 06:11.371
♪♪

06:11.371 --> 06:13.373
‐Mm.

06:13.373 --> 06:22.703
♪♪

06:22.703 --> 06:24.825
‐Weather?
‐Weather is a go.

06:24.825 --> 06:26.306
No constraints for launch.

06:26.306 --> 06:28.909
‐TDL weather.
‐Flight, the only TIL center,

06:28.909 --> 06:31.391
beginning in launch window 1‐A.
Crosswind of the others

06:31.391 --> 06:33.393
are out of limit.
‐Okay, let's wait and see

06:33.393 --> 06:36.076
how things progress.

06:36.076 --> 06:38.799
‐Are we go for crew to
proceed to the launch pad?

06:38.799 --> 06:40.561
‐We are a go.

06:40.561 --> 06:48.649
♪♪

06:48.649 --> 06:52.012
[ Indistinct talking ]

06:52.012 --> 07:00.100
♪♪

07:00.100 --> 07:08.188
♪♪

07:08.188 --> 07:16.276
♪♪

07:16.276 --> 07:18.078
‐Flight crew has arrived
at pad surface

07:18.078 --> 07:19.800
and are entering the elevators.

07:19.800 --> 07:21.802
‐Copy. Range?

07:21.802 --> 07:23.884
‐On stage,
confirm that we are a go.

07:23.884 --> 07:27.047
‐Weather continues to look
very good.

07:27.047 --> 07:28.689
‐Shallow seas.

07:28.689 --> 07:30.571
‐If we go 10 minutes later we'll
have two‐way as well.

07:30.571 --> 07:33.373
‐Copy. Let's give crew
maximum flexibility.

07:33.373 --> 07:35.856
Wait 10 to 15.
‐Copy. That should do it.

07:39.540 --> 07:43.624
‐In just a minute, you'll see
them coming across.

07:43.624 --> 07:46.306
‐Copy.
[ Speaking indistinctly ]

07:46.306 --> 07:48.589
Awaiting report.

07:48.589 --> 07:52.993
‐Standby process to RL.
‐Copy.

07:52.993 --> 07:55.636
‐FPM sealing tank,
pressurization complete.

07:55.636 --> 07:58.198
‐Copy that.

07:58.198 --> 08:01.481
‐[ Speaking indistinctly ]

08:01.481 --> 08:05.606
♪♪

08:05.606 --> 08:13.373
♪♪

08:13.373 --> 08:21.141
♪♪

08:21.141 --> 08:28.949
♪♪

08:28.949 --> 08:36.717
♪♪

08:36.717 --> 08:44.525
♪♪

08:44.525 --> 08:52.252
♪♪

08:52.252 --> 09:00.060
♪♪

09:00.060 --> 09:07.828
♪♪

09:07.828 --> 09:11.391
♪♪

09:11.391 --> 09:13.313
[ Dog whimpers, pants ]

09:15.636 --> 09:17.157
‐What do you think?

09:17.157 --> 09:20.360
[ Dog whimpers ]

09:20.360 --> 09:21.562
Fuck it.

09:21.562 --> 09:23.203
Call CAPCOM.
Secure line.

09:23.203 --> 09:25.846
‐Calling CAPCOM, secure line.

09:25.846 --> 09:27.407
[ Tone rings ]

09:27.407 --> 09:29.970
‐Sir.

09:29.970 --> 09:32.813
‐Patch him to me.

09:32.813 --> 09:35.816
‐Roger that.
[ Clears throat ]

09:35.816 --> 09:38.338
He wants 30 seconds
with the crew, non‐public.

09:38.338 --> 09:39.740
‐What for?

09:39.740 --> 09:41.902
‐Uh, just some words,
wish them luck.

09:41.902 --> 09:44.064
LC says they can swing it.

09:46.587 --> 09:48.709
We owe him as much.

09:48.709 --> 09:50.190
‐Fine.

09:50.190 --> 09:51.712
‐That's a go.

09:51.712 --> 09:54.875
‐Stand by. We'll have a window
in just a moment.

09:56.837 --> 09:59.199
Putting you through now.

09:59.199 --> 10:01.802
Matt, we've got a surprise
for you all.

10:01.802 --> 10:03.724
‐Please don't tell me we have
a weather hold.

10:03.724 --> 10:06.486
‐[ Radio crackles ]
‐Skies couldn't be clearer.

10:06.486 --> 10:08.969
‐Hags, is that you?
‐Last time I checked.

10:08.969 --> 10:12.212
‐Well, hot damn.
This is a nice surprise.

10:12.212 --> 10:13.413
‐How y'all doing in there?

10:13.413 --> 10:16.216
‐Snug as bugs.

10:16.216 --> 10:18.539
‐Well, I just called
to say Godspeed.

10:18.539 --> 10:23.504
I'm watching...
and I'm with you in spirit.

10:23.504 --> 10:26.827
‐How we looking on TV?

10:26.827 --> 10:29.229
‐Real good. Even Kwame.

10:29.229 --> 10:31.552
[ Laughter ]

10:31.552 --> 10:33.353
‐You mean you don't
miss the mustache?

10:33.353 --> 10:34.635
‐[ Chuckles ]

10:34.635 --> 10:36.517
Not for a second.

10:36.517 --> 10:40.480
‐Any final words of advice?
‐Just do whatever Mattie says.

10:40.480 --> 10:43.724
‐Listen to the man.
‐And don't clog the shitter.

10:43.724 --> 10:45.125
[ Laughter ]

10:45.125 --> 10:46.687
‐He's talking to you, Lou.

10:46.687 --> 10:48.288
‐I guess, so I'm never gonna live
that down, huh?

10:48.288 --> 10:51.852
‐Not for another 2 1/2 years.
‐Yeah, thanks, Tom.

10:51.852 --> 10:55.936
‐Sorry to break up the party,
but we need to clear the line.

10:55.936 --> 10:57.698
‐All right, you guys,
nothing sentimental here.

10:57.698 --> 11:00.220
Just do your thing.

11:00.220 --> 11:01.982
You got this.

11:01.982 --> 11:04.825
‐Means a lot, Tom ‐‐
you calling us.

11:04.825 --> 11:08.749
‐Never mind that.
Now, go make some history.

11:10.791 --> 11:13.273
‐And we're off.

11:13.273 --> 11:16.076
‐Thank you. End call.

11:16.076 --> 11:17.878
[ Tone rings ]

11:25.405 --> 11:27.007
[ Groans ]

11:27.007 --> 11:28.729
[ Dog approaches ]

11:28.729 --> 11:31.331
[ Sighs ]

11:31.331 --> 11:33.013
Well...

11:33.013 --> 11:35.856
tell me you wouldn't have
missed me if I'd gone.

11:42.783 --> 11:48.589
♪♪

11:48.589 --> 11:50.070
‐Pressure.

11:50.070 --> 11:53.994
‐Pressure steady at 15 32.
‐Systems A.

11:53.994 --> 11:56.196
‐Systems A go.
‐Systems B.

11:56.196 --> 11:58.519
‐Systems B go.
‐Systems backup.

11:58.519 --> 12:00.881
‐Backup go.
‐Weather.

12:00.881 --> 12:03.283
‐Weather is still observed
and forecast to be go.

12:03.283 --> 12:07.247
♪♪

12:07.247 --> 12:10.811
‐Listen, you guys, uh,
I just want to say, it's...

12:10.811 --> 12:13.493
it's an honor to share
this tin can with you all.

12:13.493 --> 12:15.936
‐Ah, don't make us puke
before we get up there.

12:15.936 --> 12:19.259
‐[ Laughter ]
‐No, I mean it.

12:19.259 --> 12:21.341
Seriously, I couldn't ask
for a better crew.

12:21.341 --> 12:24.505
♪♪

12:24.505 --> 12:28.388
‐T‐minus 9 poll is complete.
Resume count on my mark.

12:28.388 --> 12:32.392
3, 2, 1, mark.

12:32.392 --> 12:35.035
‐GLS auto‐sequence
has been initiated.

12:35.035 --> 12:37.077
♪♪

12:37.077 --> 12:40.360
‐Okay, Mattie, we're feeling
pretty good down here.

12:40.360 --> 12:42.122
On behalf of everyone
on the ground,

12:42.122 --> 12:44.484
it's an honor to assist
as you embark

12:44.484 --> 12:47.528
on the longest journey
any humans have ever taken.

12:47.528 --> 12:49.409
Matt...

12:49.409 --> 12:51.091
Luis...

12:51.091 --> 12:52.492
Adrienne...

12:52.492 --> 12:53.974
Cathleen...

12:53.974 --> 12:55.175
Kwame...

12:55.175 --> 12:56.857
Godspeed, good luck.

12:56.857 --> 12:58.939
Try to have a little fun
up there.

12:58.939 --> 13:01.582
‐You guys make that easy.
And thanks.

13:01.582 --> 13:05.305
Thanks to you, and thanks to
the thousands of men and women

13:05.305 --> 13:07.828
who give their souls,
their hearts,

13:07.828 --> 13:11.512
and their lives
in the cause of exploration.

13:11.512 --> 13:15.636
Okay, let's light this fire.
Providence is ready to launch.

13:15.636 --> 13:18.398
‐Thank you, sir.
Let's get going.

13:18.398 --> 13:20.240
‐That was a very nice
speech, Matthew.

13:20.240 --> 13:21.481
‐Yeah, fuck off.

13:21.481 --> 13:22.883
‐Did you write that
all by yourself?

13:22.883 --> 13:25.405
‐Hell no!
Ellen wrote that for my ass.

13:25.405 --> 13:27.528
‐Of course she did.
‐Hey, what can I say?

13:27.528 --> 13:28.969
I married up.

13:28.969 --> 13:31.211
‐90 seconds, people.

13:31.211 --> 13:34.535
♪♪

13:34.535 --> 13:36.416
‐White Room's pulling back.

13:36.416 --> 13:39.499
♪♪

13:39.499 --> 13:42.903
‐Here we go, folks.
One minute downstairs.

13:42.903 --> 13:44.945
‐You getting nervous?
‐Do I look nervous?

13:44.945 --> 13:46.747
[ Chuckling ]

13:46.747 --> 13:49.429
‐Cabin pressure is probably
gonna give us an alarm.

13:49.429 --> 13:51.712
‐LOX and hydrogen‐filling
valves are closed.

13:51.712 --> 13:53.313
‐[ Alarm sounds ]
‐And there it goes.

13:53.313 --> 13:54.955
‐Disregard.
‐Copy.

13:54.955 --> 13:57.558
‐T‐minus 30 seconds.
‐Range green.

13:57.558 --> 14:00.280
‐Stable at step 3.
Status check.

14:00.280 --> 14:02.963
‐Providence is a go.
‐Launch team is go for launch.

14:02.963 --> 14:05.646
Handoff to Providence
computers has occurred.

14:05.646 --> 14:08.448
Solid rocket booster nozzle
steering check in work.

14:08.448 --> 14:10.170
‐15.
‐Let's do it.

14:10.170 --> 14:15.576
‐Go for main engine start.
T‐minus 10, 9, 8,

14:15.576 --> 14:20.220
‐[ Whoosh ]
‐...7, 6, 5, 4...

14:20.220 --> 14:21.221
‐Four at 100.

14:21.221 --> 14:23.263
‐...3, 2, 1...

14:23.263 --> 14:30.671
♪♪

14:30.671 --> 14:32.112
‐There goes tower.

14:32.112 --> 14:37.237
♪♪

14:37.237 --> 14:39.640
‐We have liftoff
for Providence 1.

14:39.640 --> 14:42.803
[ Rumbling ]

14:42.803 --> 14:45.485
And thus marks an
historic moment for humanity ‐‐

14:45.485 --> 14:47.367
the first manned mission
to Mars

14:47.367 --> 14:49.289
launching
to escape Earth's gravity

14:49.289 --> 14:51.491
on a voyage to the red planet.

14:51.491 --> 14:53.814
The dreams of billions
are with them.

14:56.216 --> 14:58.098
‐Four at 104.

14:59.660 --> 15:03.143
‐Vista, roll program.
‐Roger. Roll, Providence.

15:03.143 --> 15:06.507
♪♪

15:06.507 --> 15:08.148
‐Four at 72.

15:10.591 --> 15:13.914
‐Go, you son of a bitch.

15:13.914 --> 15:16.116
‐Looking good from here,
Providence.

15:16.116 --> 15:17.958
Throttle up to 104.

15:17.958 --> 15:19.760
‐Roger go. Throttle up.

15:19.760 --> 15:21.481
‐Standby for staging.

15:21.481 --> 15:29.449
♪♪

15:29.449 --> 15:37.417
♪♪

15:37.417 --> 15:45.385
♪♪

15:45.385 --> 15:53.353
♪♪

15:53.353 --> 15:55.556
[ Ominous music plays ]

15:55.556 --> 16:01.562
♪♪

16:01.562 --> 16:03.764
[ Metallic warbling ]

16:03.764 --> 16:10.731
♪♪

16:10.731 --> 16:13.013
‐The dirt beneath our feet...

16:13.013 --> 16:16.176
♪♪

16:16.176 --> 16:20.020
...it pulls down on every step.

16:20.020 --> 16:21.381
[ Ding ]

16:21.381 --> 16:24.585
♪♪

16:24.585 --> 16:26.827
It brings everything
back to the center.

16:26.827 --> 16:28.268
[ Coin clatters, echoes ]

16:28.268 --> 16:37.518
♪♪

16:37.518 --> 16:41.081
[ Screaming, shouting ]

16:41.081 --> 16:50.090
♪♪

16:50.090 --> 16:52.893
‐There is confusion in
the grandstands here

16:52.893 --> 16:54.134
at the liftoff of Providence 1.

16:54.134 --> 16:55.656
‐Call Kayla.
‐I'm being told

16:55.656 --> 16:58.458
that Mission Control
will be reviewing what...

16:58.458 --> 17:00.661
‐All circuits are busy.

17:00.661 --> 17:02.182
‐Try again.

17:02.182 --> 17:06.466
‐[ Busy signal ]
‐All circuits are busy.

17:06.466 --> 17:08.468
‐Try again.

17:08.468 --> 17:11.271
‐[ Busy signal ]
‐All circuits are busy.

17:11.271 --> 17:13.353
‐Try again!

17:13.353 --> 17:15.956
Open!

17:15.956 --> 17:18.398
[ Tires squeal ]

17:18.398 --> 17:26.647
♪♪

17:26.647 --> 17:34.855
♪♪

17:34.855 --> 17:43.143
♪♪

17:43.143 --> 17:46.226
Folks, all of this has got to go
before the families arrive.

17:46.226 --> 17:49.590
♪♪

17:49.590 --> 17:52.633
Champagne.
Get the champagne off the table.

17:52.633 --> 17:57.237
♪♪

17:57.237 --> 18:00.200
Coming through.

18:00.200 --> 18:02.362
[ Sirens chirp ]

18:02.362 --> 18:07.327
♪♪

18:07.327 --> 18:09.329
[ Doors open, close ]

18:09.329 --> 18:17.778
♪♪

18:17.778 --> 18:19.339
‐Don't say anything.

18:19.339 --> 18:20.541
Are they all ready?

18:20.541 --> 18:22.663
‐Everyone's ready.
‐Thank you.

18:22.663 --> 18:31.471
♪♪

18:31.471 --> 18:33.874
‐State and Defense
have been notified.

18:33.874 --> 18:35.996
Got a call with
the president in 10.

18:35.996 --> 18:39.520
‐Well, then, let's speak after.

18:39.520 --> 18:40.801
I need to...

18:40.801 --> 18:42.042
‐Okay.

18:48.689 --> 18:51.171
‐Everyone,
your attention, please.

18:51.171 --> 18:53.534
[ Footsteps echoing ]

19:12.032 --> 19:16.196
‐Our machine...failed us.

19:20.841 --> 19:28.248
Five brave explorers
have been lost.

19:31.211 --> 19:36.937
And, um, as much as we all knew
that was a possibility...

19:39.980 --> 19:44.304
...I'm, um...

19:44.304 --> 19:49.550
I'm utterly shocked, as I'm sure
all of you are, as well.

19:52.272 --> 19:56.116
We have counselors available
for anyone who needs them.

19:56.116 --> 20:00.641
And, in fact, any of your needs,
please take them to HR.

20:03.764 --> 20:11.732
The most important thing
is that we support one another

20:11.732 --> 20:14.935
as a team, and, um...

20:19.620 --> 20:23.303
...that we d‐don't descend
into despair.

20:32.432 --> 20:34.114
‐This is the moment.

20:36.837 --> 20:39.479
‐No alarm at separation?

20:39.479 --> 20:41.522
‐It has to be
the booster separation motors.

20:41.522 --> 20:43.243
The outer shell should have been
able to withstand

20:43.243 --> 20:46.326
at least 50,000 pounds of
blast pressure from each motor.

20:46.326 --> 20:48.769
We had three layers
of redundancy.

20:50.450 --> 20:53.614
If there was any kind of
mechanical malfunction

20:53.614 --> 20:55.856
or pressure deviation,

20:55.856 --> 20:57.938
the automatic abort
would have initiated.

20:57.938 --> 21:00.380
It just doesn't ‐‐
doesn't make sense.

21:00.380 --> 21:01.902
How can we have
a separation malfunction

21:01.902 --> 21:06.466
without any data
showing any abnormality?

21:06.466 --> 21:08.268
If we had a sensor issue
with one of the motors,

21:08.268 --> 21:09.750
the other ones would've
picked it up.

21:09.750 --> 21:11.712
That's what I don't understand.

21:11.712 --> 21:14.595
We've modeled thousands
of different scenarios.

21:14.595 --> 21:17.437
I‐I can't even imagine
what we might have missed.

21:17.437 --> 21:20.360
‐Could you give us a second,
please?

21:20.360 --> 21:21.762
‐Sure.

21:31.732 --> 21:33.574
‐You can't put this
on yourself.

21:35.936 --> 21:37.778
‐It was my design.

21:37.778 --> 21:40.340
‐There were thousands of people
involved in that design.

21:40.340 --> 21:42.062
‐And I led them.

21:42.062 --> 21:45.506
‐And they need a leader now.

21:45.506 --> 21:47.227
We need to keep it together.

21:49.590 --> 21:51.552
If we do, then they will.

21:53.433 --> 21:55.395
What can I do?
H‐How can I help?

22:00.320 --> 22:02.963
‐I'm all right.
‐Are you sure?

22:02.963 --> 22:05.005
‐Yeah.

22:05.005 --> 22:08.849
Yeah, I'll get the booster team
at the build facility,

22:08.849 --> 22:10.891
get some eyes on the hardware.

22:13.694 --> 22:15.335
‐Okay, thank you, everyone.

22:15.335 --> 22:17.377
Let's stop the work
till the families get through.

22:24.745 --> 22:27.107
Tried to call.
‐Lines were jammed.

22:27.107 --> 22:30.070
‐Green room's ready.
‐Thank you.

22:35.756 --> 22:38.799
‐[ Sobs ]

22:38.799 --> 22:44.645
♪♪

22:44.645 --> 22:50.531
♪♪

22:50.531 --> 22:52.012
‐Hey, you.

22:52.012 --> 23:01.542
♪♪

23:06.266 --> 23:08.468
[ Indistinct talking ]

23:19.520 --> 23:21.081
‐You hungry?

23:21.081 --> 23:23.003
‐I'm...

23:23.003 --> 23:25.405
No. Thanks.

23:25.405 --> 23:27.247
‐How about you? You hungry?

23:27.247 --> 23:28.969
Yeah?
Come here.

23:30.771 --> 23:34.815
Last time I saw you,
you were about that big.

23:34.815 --> 23:36.697
Here.

23:36.697 --> 23:38.498
[ Chair scrapes ]

23:41.061 --> 23:43.263
Climb up there.

23:45.185 --> 23:48.549
‐You're an astronaut, like Dad?

23:48.549 --> 23:51.351
‐I used to be.

23:51.351 --> 23:53.473
You like ham?

23:53.473 --> 23:56.156
How about chicken?

23:56.156 --> 23:57.798
My daughter
doesn't like meat, either,

23:57.798 --> 23:59.520
so watch what we'll do here.

24:01.762 --> 24:03.003
And this...

24:04.885 --> 24:09.089
And now you've got...

24:09.089 --> 24:12.613
a double‐cheese sandwich.

24:15.295 --> 24:16.657
There you go.

24:19.700 --> 24:21.702
‐Who gets to decide?

24:21.702 --> 24:24.264
‐To decide what?

24:24.264 --> 24:25.986
‐Who dies.

24:31.992 --> 24:33.794
‐Here.

24:33.794 --> 24:35.596
I'll show you something.

24:41.281 --> 24:42.643
‐[ Laughs ]

24:42.643 --> 24:44.885
‐Your turn.

24:48.208 --> 24:49.730
Perfect. Okay.

24:49.730 --> 24:51.892
You want to take it back
and sit with your mom?

24:54.655 --> 24:58.498
‐Did you ask him to come?
‐He was here when we arrived.

24:58.498 --> 25:00.581
It would mean a lot to them
that he's here.

25:00.581 --> 25:01.942
Do you want to talk to him?

25:01.942 --> 25:03.784
‐No.

25:03.784 --> 25:05.145
And the families?

25:05.145 --> 25:07.187
‐Yeah, well...

25:07.187 --> 25:09.790
We're gonna wait an hour or so
before they get briefed.

25:09.790 --> 25:12.072
‐Well, whatever
you think is best.

25:12.072 --> 25:14.795
‐Anything I can tell them?
‐Not right now. Um...

25:17.037 --> 25:18.839
I'll check in later.

25:18.839 --> 25:19.840
End call.

25:19.840 --> 25:22.202
[ Tone rings ]

25:22.202 --> 25:24.364
‐He waves his finger at me.

25:24.364 --> 25:27.528
"Mom, I'm going to be
too big to fit in my seat."

25:27.528 --> 25:32.372
I say, "You'll thank me. I know
how bad this freeze‐dry is."

25:32.372 --> 25:34.655
Then after dinner,
we have presents...

25:38.779 --> 25:40.901
...for the birthdays
he'll be gone.

25:44.825 --> 25:47.387
He says, "No. Bad luck."

25:47.387 --> 25:49.029
I say, "No such thing ‐‐"

25:49.029 --> 25:50.591
‐Will you stop?

25:52.913 --> 25:54.595
I need a drink.

25:54.595 --> 25:56.637
They have nothing to drink.

26:11.331 --> 26:13.493
‐[ Sobs ]

26:19.179 --> 26:21.982
‐Translating to the SSU.
How they driving?

26:21.982 --> 26:23.704
‐So far, so good.

26:23.704 --> 26:26.186
Got that last turn on AP Alpha,
moving on.

26:27.668 --> 26:29.109
[ Static, beep ]

26:29.109 --> 26:31.471
‐Luis, we copy your checks
on AP Alpha.

26:31.471 --> 26:34.314
Next will be AP Bravo H2.

26:34.314 --> 26:35.716
‐Copy.

26:35.716 --> 26:40.961
♪♪

26:40.961 --> 26:44.645
‐Luis, wave to the folks
back home.

26:44.645 --> 26:52.653
♪♪

26:52.653 --> 26:56.496
Hey. Take a look.

26:56.496 --> 26:59.419
‐Man, wish we could do this
every day.

26:59.419 --> 27:01.341
Never gets old.

27:01.341 --> 27:02.743
‐Never.

27:02.743 --> 27:04.785
♪♪

27:04.785 --> 27:07.788
‐Gentlemen, heads up
for sunset.

27:07.788 --> 27:09.269
‐Roger, Vista.

27:09.269 --> 27:12.072
We'll finish up here
and start heading back.

27:12.072 --> 27:17.317
♪♪

27:17.317 --> 27:19.840
‐Lucky bastards, aren't we?

27:19.840 --> 27:23.203
‐Pause.

27:23.203 --> 27:24.965
[ Clunk ]

27:24.965 --> 27:27.207
[ Footsteps depart ]

27:39.499 --> 27:40.821
[ Door closes ]

27:40.821 --> 27:42.823
‐If you can sign it tonight,
great.

27:42.823 --> 27:45.145
Or take it home and run it past
your personal counsel.

27:45.145 --> 27:46.507
‐I'll leave this here.

27:46.507 --> 27:48.188
‐Either way,
if you have any questions

27:48.188 --> 27:50.190
or your counsel wants to
reach out, we are on standby...

27:50.190 --> 27:52.913
‐Have you spoken to Laz?
‐A little while ago.

27:52.913 --> 27:55.075
‐Well, is she coming?
‐I don't know.

27:55.075 --> 27:57.558
She said she's at a meeting.

27:57.558 --> 28:00.360
‐She should be here.
‐Well, I agree.

28:00.360 --> 28:08.609
♪♪

28:08.609 --> 28:11.011
[ Footsteps echo ]

28:11.011 --> 28:21.212
♪♪

28:21.212 --> 28:22.865
[ knocking ]

28:22.865 --> 28:29.309
♪♪

28:29.309 --> 28:31.151
‐I'll be back in a minute.

28:31.151 --> 28:34.114
♪♪

28:34.114 --> 28:36.036
My office.

28:36.036 --> 28:41.722
♪♪

28:41.722 --> 28:44.404
You could have called.
‐You wouldn't have answered.

28:44.404 --> 28:46.647
‐What is it? We're in the middle
of a briefing meeting ‐‐

28:46.647 --> 28:48.328
‐You know that
they're loading soon.

28:48.328 --> 28:49.570
‐Yeah.

28:49.570 --> 28:52.132
‐Well, you need to
say something.

28:52.132 --> 28:54.014
‐We still don't know
what happened.

28:54.014 --> 28:55.536
‐I'm ‐‐
I'm not talking about answers.

28:55.536 --> 28:57.337
You've got to give them
more than lawyers.

28:57.337 --> 28:58.899
‐You know the protocol.
‐Screw the protocol.

28:58.899 --> 29:02.182
You got to shoulder
some responsibility here.

29:02.182 --> 29:03.664
‐That's exactly what I'm doing.

29:03.664 --> 29:05.586
‐I mean with the families.

29:08.909 --> 29:11.071
‐Why are you inserting
yourself into this?

29:11.071 --> 29:12.993
‐Because I know them.

29:12.993 --> 29:15.636
'Cause I selected them,
I trained them.

29:15.636 --> 29:17.237
Because I was supposed
to be able to ‐‐

29:17.237 --> 29:18.519
‐They have crew assigned.

29:18.519 --> 29:20.320
Everything is being
taken care of.

29:20.320 --> 29:23.123
‐Crew's not the same as you.

29:23.123 --> 29:24.965
They need to hear from you.

29:24.965 --> 29:26.166
‐And say what?

29:26.166 --> 29:28.128
‐Show them that
it fucking hurts.

29:32.813 --> 29:34.014
‐Of course it hurts.

29:34.014 --> 29:35.616
‐So show them that.

29:38.218 --> 29:40.380
‐You're not helping. I know you
think you are, but you're not.

29:40.380 --> 29:42.102
‐Why are you afraid of them?

29:42.102 --> 29:44.264
Why can't you look them
in the eye?

29:44.264 --> 29:46.426
‐I have a briefing
to get back to.

29:46.426 --> 29:48.228
‐It can wait.
‐No, it can't, actually.

29:48.228 --> 29:50.390
And this is holding things up.

29:51.792 --> 29:52.953
‐Coward.

29:56.717 --> 29:57.958
‐Fine.

30:07.007 --> 30:09.089
[ Indistinct talking ]

30:20.741 --> 30:26.466
‐My first year at NASA ‐‐
Columbia happens.

30:26.466 --> 30:29.189
That was pure hell.

30:29.189 --> 30:31.111
That's when I started smoking.

30:32.993 --> 30:34.515
‐I didn't know you did.

30:34.515 --> 30:36.436
‐Well, I quit.

30:36.436 --> 30:38.759
But I always bring one
to a launch.

30:40.561 --> 30:42.202
‐Oh, no, thanks.

30:51.051 --> 30:53.974
‐You do know how ugly
this is gonna get, right?

30:55.896 --> 30:57.497
‐It looks fine.

31:01.421 --> 31:03.263
[ Water running ]

31:20.681 --> 31:22.442
[ Exhales sharply ]

31:33.974 --> 31:36.416
‐You want me to drive you home?
‐No. It's okay.

31:36.416 --> 31:39.540
‐Are you sure?
‐Yeah.

31:39.540 --> 31:41.622
I really appreciate it, Tom.

31:43.423 --> 31:45.706
‐I am so sorry for your loss.

31:48.188 --> 31:49.670
‐Thank you.

31:54.555 --> 31:57.598
‐Ellen, anything 24/7.

31:57.598 --> 32:00.681
‐I'm so sorry for your loss.

32:00.681 --> 32:02.242
‐This is obscene.

32:04.565 --> 32:07.047
What did she lose, huh?
Tell me.

32:07.047 --> 32:09.730
She lost nothing.

32:09.730 --> 32:10.771
‐Come on, let's go.

32:10.771 --> 32:13.213
‐Huh? How much did you make?

32:13.213 --> 32:15.255
‐Let him go!
‐Let's go outside.

32:15.255 --> 32:17.778
‐Please.
‐I know you're feeling ‐‐

32:17.778 --> 32:19.219
‐What do you know?!

32:19.219 --> 32:20.781
‐Guillermo, please!

32:20.781 --> 32:22.462
‐Come on, tell me!

32:22.462 --> 32:24.545
Then <i>you</i> tell me!
You tell me! You tell me!

32:28.348 --> 32:31.031
[ Light music plays ]

32:31.031 --> 32:39.479
♪♪

32:39.479 --> 32:47.888
♪♪

